{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9973da604e18ef82", "type": "tool_result", "content": "100\tthe main benefit of extra context in technicaltalk SimulST comes from paper-specific terminology recovery, while uniform context injection can be unreliable.\n101\t• We propose EGTA, an evidence-grounded terminology adaptation framework that restricts\n102\tinference-time adaptation to compact candidate terms selected from document context\n103\tand the current streaming state.\n104\t• We analyze EGTA across end-to-end, cascaded, and generation-only backbones, showing where terminology adaptation provides\n105\tthe most headroom without full-model finetuning.\n106\t\n107\t• Experiments on an ACL technical-talk evaluation suite show consistent improvements\n108\tin XCOMET-XL, named-entity recall, and\n109\tacronym recall, with external ACL60/60-dev\n110\tvalidation and grounding audits supporting\n111\tpaper-specific evidence alignment.\n112\t\n113\t2\n114\t\n115\tRelated Work\n116\t\n117\t2.1\n118\t\n119\tSimultaneous Speech Translation\n120\t\n121\tSimultaneous speech translation (SimulST) requires balancing quality and latency while the\n122\tsource speech is still unfolding. Prior work has\n123\tstudied read/write policies such as wait-k, monotonic attention, and information-transport policies,\n124\tas well as evaluation toolkits and latency metrics\n125\tsuch as SimulEval and length-adaptive average lagging (Ma et al., 2019; Arivazhagan et al., 2019;\n126\tMa et al., 2020; Zhang and Feng, 2022; Papi et al.,\n127\t2022). These methods primarily improve segmentation, policy learning, or latency-aware decoding.\n128\tOur work is complementary: we study how to\n129\tuse extra document context when only a subset\n130\tof streaming segments requires paper-specific terminology.\n131\t2.2\n132\t\n133\tContext-Aware and Terminology-Aware\n134\tTranslation\n135\t\n136\tContext-aware translation has been widely studied in document-level MT and ST, including priorsentence context, document-level context, and analyses of whether models actually use contextual\n137\tsignals (Voita et al., 2018; Maruf et al., 2019, 2021;\n138\tZhang et al., 2021; Dabre et al., 2021; Fernandes\n139\tet al., 2021). Terminology adaptation has also been\n140\tstudied through lexical constraints, dictionary injection, terminology-aware training, and vocabulary\n141\tbiasing (Hokamp and Liu, 2017; Post and Vilar,\n142\t2018; Dinu et al., 2019). These works show that\n143\tbroader context or external lexical knowledge can\n144\timprove translation, especially in domain-specific\n145\tsettings.\n146\tSimulST creates a different challenge: context\n147\tmust be useful before the full utterance or document is observed. Uniformly injecting all document terms into every segment may expose the\n148\tmodel to irrelevant context and encourage hallucinated terminology. EGTA therefore differs from\n149\tgeneral document-context methods by treating context as a sparse terminology memory and activating\n150\tit only when the current speech stream provides\n151\tsupporting evidence.\n152\t\n153\t\f2.3\n154\t\n155\tSpeech-Language Models and Contextual\n156\tBiasing\n157\t\n158\tEnd-to-end speech translation and speech-language\n159\tmodels, including Translatotron, SpeechT5, and\n160\tSeamlessM4T, directly map speech to target text\n161\tor unify speech and text modeling (Jia et al., 2019;\n162\tAo et al., 2022; Barrault et al., 2023). In speech\n163\trecognition, contextual biasing and hotwording are\n164\tcommonly used to improve recognition of rare\n165\tnames, technical terms, and personalized vocabulary (Pundak et al., 2018). EGTA connects these\n166\tideas by decomposing terminology adaptation into\n167\tASR/speech-side and decoder-side decision spaces,\n168\tinstead of treating document context as a uniform\n169\tsignal applied to every segment.\n170\tIn contrast to prior context-aware SimulST work\n171\tthat studies whether context helps at the sentence or\n172\tdocument level, our focus is when context should\n173\tbe activated during streaming inference. EGTA operationalizes this question as terminology-memory\n174\tconstruction, evidence-conditioned candidate selection, and architecture-specific ASR/speech-side\n175\tand decoder-side adaptation.\n176\t\n177\t3\n178\t\n179\tMethod\n180\t\n181\tFigure 1 shows the two-stage EGTA workflow.\n182\tThis section specifies the terminology memory, the\n183\tevidence-conditioned selection algorithm, and the\n184\tconcrete R/G adaptation interfaces used in our systems.\n185\t3.1\n186\t\n187\tProblem Setup\n188\t\n189\tGiven an input speech stream X, a SimulST system incrementally receives audio chunks and emits\n190\ttarget-language text before the full utterance or talk\n191\tis observed. For a streaming segment i, the system\n192\tobserves partial speech input X≤i and produces\n193\ttarget output Yi . In technical talks, we additionally\n194\tassume access to document-level context D, such\n195\tas the paper title, abstract, glossary, or automatically extracted metadata.\n196\tThe goal is to use D to improve terminology\n197\tfidelity without introducing irrelevant terms into\n198\tsegments where the context is not needed. A naive\n199\tapproach is to concatenate the whole document\n200\tcontext to every streaming input. However, this\n201\ttreats all segments as equally context-dependent.\n202\tEGTA instead treats document context as a sparse\n203\tterminology source and restricts adaptation to a\n204\tsegment-specific candidate subset.\n205\t\n206\t3.2\n207\t\n208\tTerminology Memory\n209\t\n210\tEGTA converts document context D into a terminology memory TD = {t1 , . . . , tm } containing\n211\tpaper-specific terms that are difficult for speech\n212\ttranslation, including acronyms, model and dataset\n213\tnames, method names, organization names, and\n214\ttechnical phrases. The memory is not taken from\n215\tan IWSLT-provided gold glossary. We construct\n216\tit automatically from paper-level context, including titles, abstracts, and available metadata, using a prompt-based Qwen3-30B-Instruct extractor\n217\tserved in FP8. The extractor proposes candidate\n218\tnamed entities and technical terms, after which\n219\twe normalize terms by case, punctuation, whitespace, and hyphen variants. We keep acronymlike strings, alphanumeric or hyphenated technical\n220\tnames, CamelCase terms, and multi-word technical phrases, while filtering generic function words\n221\tand non-technical metadata. Candidate named entities are therefore treated as a noisy terminology\n222\tlist rather than a gold inventory; EGTA uses local\n223\tspeech evidence to select from this list instead of\n224\ttrusting every extracted term. Each term stores\n225\tsurface forms and tokenizer-level variants for both\n226\tASR/speech-side conditioning and decoder-side token biasing. Appendix A.2 reports memory-size\n227\tand term-type statistics.\n228\t3.3\n229\t\n230\tEvidence-Conditioned Candidate\n231\tSelection\n232\t\n233\tFor each streaming segment, EGTA selects a compact subset of terms from the document memory.\n234\tLet Ei denote the local evidence for segment i,\n235\tincluding the current speech segment, partial transcript or ASR hypothesis, nearby history, and partial target-side state. EGTA forms\n236\tTi = A(TD , Ei ),\n237\t\n238\t(1)\n239\t\n240\twhere A(·) is the deterministic inference-time procedure in Algorithm 1. The selector normalizes Ei\n241\twith the same rules as TD , matches surface forms,\n242\tacronyms, and tokenizer-level variants, and ranks\n243\tmatches by exactness, specificity, and recency under a fixed per-segment terminology budget. If the\n244\tcurrent partial hypothesis contains “we evaluate on\n245\tMCIF”, for example, the mention of “MCIF” is\n246\tan evidence event that activates the memory term\n247\tMCIF. Detailed matching rules and prompt formatting are given in Appendix A.3.\n248\tRunning example. Consider a segment whose\n249\tpartial ASR hypothesis contains “we evaluate on\n250\t\n251\t\fFigure 1: Overview of EGTA. The bottom panel shows the preparation stage, where document context is converted\n252\toffline into a compact terminology memory. The top panel shows the inference stage: EGTA extracts local evidence\n253\tfrom the current streaming segment, matches it to the terminology memory, selects evidence-supported terms, and\n254\tuses them as inference-time conditioning signals for ASR-side, speech-encoder-side, and decoder-side decisions.\n255\tLocal evidence refers to a cue from the current segment, such as a partial transcript or ASR hypothesis that matches\n256\ta term in the terminology memory.\n257\t\n258\tMCIF” while the document memory contains terms\n259\tsuch as MCIF, SimulEval, and Qwen3-Omni. The\n260\tselector treats the observed mention of MCIF as\n261\tlocal evidence, ranks it above unmatched memory terms, and exposes only the selected set to the\n262\tdownstream interfaces. EGTA-R inserts the selected terms into the compact terminology context\n263\tor ASR hotword list, while EGTA-G biases only\n264\tthe corresponding decoder tokens. Unmatched\n265\tmemory terms remain available for later segments\n266\tbut are not activated for the current one.\n267\tThe selected terms define what is exposed to\n268\tASR/speech-side conditioning and decoder-side\n269\tbiasing, but realization is still determined by the\n270\tspeech-conditioned decoder. We therefore use\n271\t“evidence-grounded” as a behavioral claim rather\n272\tthan a hard symbolic guarantee, and validate it\n273\tthrough activation audits, evidence-strength buckets, and shuffled-memory controls in Section 5.4.\n274\t3.4\n275\t\n276\tASR/Speech-Side and Decoder-Side\n277\tAdaptation\n278\t\n279\tEGTA applies selected terms through two interfaces: R(Ti ) for ASR/speech-side conditioning\n280\tand G(Ti ) for decoder-side biasing. EGTA-RG\n281\t\n282\tAlgorithm 1 EGTA inference for streaming segment i\n283\tRequire: document context D, streaming state Ei , terminology budget K, bias strength B\n284\t1: Build or load terminology memory TD from D\n285\t2: Normalize the ASR hypothesis, partial transcript, and\n286\trecent history in Ei\n287\t3: Match terms in TD by surface form, acronym, or\n288\ttokenizer-level variant\n289\t4: Rank matches by exact match, acronym match, specificity,\n290\tand recency\n291\t5: Select top-K evidence-supported terms Ti\n292\t6: Apply R(Ti ) as ASR hotwords or compact terminology\n293\tcontext\n294\t7: Apply G(Ti ) as decoder-side vocabulary bias with\n295\tstrength B\n296\t8: Decode the next streaming output prefix\n297\t\n298\tcombines both.\n299\tASR/speech-side adaptation. ASR/speech-side\n300\tadaptation helps the system hear or attend to relevant terminology before target decoding. In cascaded systems, R(Ti ) is implemented through ASR\n301\thotwords or contextual biasing. In end-to-end systems, R(Ti ) is implemented as inference-time terminology conditioning for the speech-language\n302\tmodel rather than as a parameter update. It exposes\n303\tonly selected terms, e.g., Relevant paper terms:\n304\t\n305\t\fMCIF; SimulEval, instead of the full document\n306\tcontext.\n307\tDecoder-side adaptation. Decoder-side adaptation preserves selected terminology during target\n308\tdecoding. For each selected term t ∈ Ti , EGTA\n309\tidentifies target-side token variants and applies a\n310\tvocabulary-level bias. Let zt (v) be the original\n311\tlogit for vocabulary token v at decoding step t.\n312\tEGTA-G modifies it as\n313\tzt′ (v) = zt (v) + B · 1[v ∈ V (Ti )],\n314\t\n315\t(2)\n316\t\n317\twhere V (Ti ) is the set of vocabulary tokens associated with the selected terms and B is the bias\n318\tstrength. Target-side variants are constructed from\n319\tthe terminology memory and tokenizer outputs,\n320\tnot from test references. This biasing rule is deliberately simple: our goal is not to introduce a new\n321\tconstrained-decoding algorithm, but to test whether\n322\tdocument terms should be activated selectively under streaming evidence. We therefore compare\n323\tEGTA-G with stronger alternatives, including uniform full-memory context and Global-G, which\n324\tapplies decoder-side bias to all memory terms without evidence-conditioned selection. As shown in\n325\tSection 5.3 and Appendix A.6, stronger all-term\n326\tbias increases over-biasing risk and can degrade\n327\tBLEU and latency, while selected-term bias gives\n328\ta better recall–quality–latency trade-off. Unlike\n329\tglobal terminology biasing, EGTA-G biases only\n330\tevidence-selected terms, limiting over-biasing on\n331\tunrelated segments.\n332\tFull EGTA-RG. When both interfaces are available, EGTA decodes with\n333\tYi = Mθ (X≤i ; R(Ti ), G(Ti )).\n334\t\n335\tR(Ti ) interface\n336\t\n337\tG(Ti ) interface\n338\t\n339\tQwen3-Omni E2E compact term context decoder logit bias\n340\tCascade ASR–MT ASR hotwords\n341\tMT vocabulary bias\n342\tSeamlessM4T\n343\t–\n344\tdecoder-side EGTA-G\n345\t\n346\tTable 1: Concrete EGTA instantiations across backbones.\n347\t\n348\t4\n349\t\n350\tExperimental Setup\n351\t\n352\t4.1\n353\t\n354\tDatasets\n355\t\n356\tWe evaluate EGTA on an ACL technical-talk\n357\tSimulST evaluation suite consisting of MCIF-dev\n358\tand ACL60/60-dev. Both subsets are built from\n359\ttechnical conference talks with paper-level context,\n360\tmaking them suitable for evaluating terminology\n361\tadaptation under streaming speech evidence.\n362\tMCIF-dev is derived from MCIF (Multimodal\n363\tCrosslingual Instruction Following), a multilingual\n364\tbenchmark based on scientific talks (Papi et al.,\n365\t2025). We pair its speech and references with\n366\tpaper-level metadata, including titles, abstracts,\n367\tand extracted terminology, and use the resulting 21talk, 919-segment technical-talk subset as the main\n368\tbenchmark for full latency, ablation, and grounding\n369\tanalyses.\n370\tACL60/60-dev is used as an external technicaltalk benchmark. It contains 5 ACL talks and 468\n371\tgold-segmented segments with official En→Zh\n372\tand En→De references. It also provides tagged\n373\tterminology for both target languages, allowing\n374\tterminology-sensitive evaluation beyond MCIFdev. We use the same terminology extraction,\n375\tnormalization, candidate selection, and EGTA-RG\n376\tB=2 configuration without additional fine-tuning.\n377\t\n378\t(3)\n379\t\n380\tHere R(Ti ) improves access to relevant terminology in the speech-understanding stage, while G(Ti )\n381\tpreserves selected terms through token-level biasing.\n382\t3.5\n383\t\n384\tBackbone\n385\t\n386\tArchitecture Instantiations\n387\t\n388\tTable 1 summarizes the concrete interfaces used in\n389\teach backbone. All instantiations share the same\n390\tselected term set Ti ; they differ only in how R(Ti )\n391\tand G(Ti ) are exposed by the model.\n392\tThe Qwen3-Omni end-to-end setting is our main\n393\tsystem. The cascade setting diagnoses how much\n394\theadroom remains when ASR-side hotwording is\n395\talready available, and SeamlessM4T provides a\n396\tgeneration-only transfer check when the R(Ti ) interface is unavailable.\n397\t\n398\t4.2\n399\t\n400\tSystems and Configurations\n401\t\n402\tFor end-to-end SimulST, we use a fine-tuned\n403\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B audio-text LLM as the\n404\tbackbone. Following our IWSLT system setup,\n405\tthe audio encoder is kept frozen, the non-text generation modules are disabled, and only languageside LoRA adapters are used to teach streaming\n406\tread/write behavior. At inference time, the backbone is served with vLLM using greedy decoding and a bounded dialogue history. The backbone checkpoint, chunk schedule, decoding parameters, and evaluation talks are fixed across variants;\n407\tvariants differ only in the inference-time terminology interface. The baseline receives the streaming\n408\tspeech input and task instruction without document\n409\tterminology adaptation. We additionally include a\n410\t\n411\t\funiform-context baseline, which injects the full perpaper terminology memory into every streaming\n412\tsegment without evidence-conditioned selection or\n413\tdecoder-side biasing. This baseline tests whether\n414\tsimply exposing document terminology to every\n415\tsegment is sufficient.\n416\tEGTA-R adds a compact terminology block selected from the document memory; EGTA-G applies decoder-side vocabulary bias to terminology tokens; and EGTA-RG combines both channels. Unless otherwise specified, our recommended\n417\tend-to-end configuration is EGTA-RG with bias\n418\tstrength B = 2.\n419\tWe also evaluate EGTA in a cascaded ASR–MT\n420\tsetting for architecture analysis. We use Qwen3ASR-1.7B as the ASR front end and pass the selected terms as ASR hotwords/contextual-biasing\n421\tterms for EGTA-R; EGTA-G is implemented\n422\tthrough MT decoder vocabulary bias. Finally, we\n423\tevaluate SeamlessM4T-v2-large as a generationonly backbone validation. Since this backbone\n424\tdoes not expose the same editable terminologyprompting interface used for EGTA-R, we instantiate only EGTA-G. To test whether gains are paperspecific, we additionally use a shuffled-memory\n425\tcontrol that pairs each segment with terminology\n426\tmemory from a mismatched paper.\n427\t4.3\n428\t\n429\tMetrics and Diagnostics\n430\t\n431\tWe report BLEU, chrF, XCOMET-XL, NERclean\n432\trecall, acronym recall, and LongLAALCU latency. BLEU and chrF measure surface overlap,\n433\tXCOMET-XL provides a neural quality estimate,\n434\tand lower LongLAALCU indicates lower latency.\n435\tNERclean recall is computed over cleaned paperspecific entities after normalizing case, punctuation,\n436\twhitespace, hyphenation, and tokenizer artifacts;\n437\tacronym recall is computed over uppercase and\n438\talphanumeric paper terms. We use terminology recall as the primary metric because omission or mistranslation of paper-specific terms is the main failure mode in technical-talk SimulST. Since surfaceform precision depends on whether a reference\n439\tpreserves the same term realization, precision/F1style matching is treated as a conservative diagnostic, while possible over-generation is analyzed\n440\tthrough unsupported-activation audits, shuffledmemory controls, and Global-G stress tests.\n441\tFor the main end-to-end experiments, we evaluate five latency operating points; the anchor point\n442\tis used for detailed comparison, ablation, and\n443\tshuffled-memory control. In addition to aggregate\n444\t\n445\tSet\n446\t\n447\tLang. ∆BLEU ∆XCOMET ∆NER ∆Acro ∆LAAL\n448\t\n449\tMCIF-dev\n450\tZh\n451\tMCIF-dev\n452\tDe\n453\tACL60/60-dev Zh\n454\tACL60/60-dev De\n455\t\n456\t+1.05\n457\t+0.59\n458\t+0.94\n459\t+0.56\n460\t\n461\t+.019\n462\t+.006\n463\t+.022\n464\t+.005\n465\t\n466\t+.212\n467\t+.266\n468\t+.113\n469\t+.214\n470\t\n471\t+.099\n472\t+.171\n473\t+.119\n474\t+.100\n475\t\n476\t-46\n477\t-44\n478\t–\n479\t–\n480\t\n481\tTable 2: Anchor-point gains of EGTA-RG B=2 over\n482\tthe baseline on the ACL technical-talk evaluation suite.\n483\tNER denotes NERclean recall. LAAL is reported\n484\tfor MCIF-dev, where the streaming-yaml protocol is\n485\tmatched across systems. Full absolute scores are reported in Appendix A.1.\n486\t\n487\tmetrics, we conduct activation audits, evidencestrength bucket analysis, and shuffled-memory controls to validate whether realized terminology usage\n488\tis supported by speech-conditioned evidence rather\n489\tthan generic context exposure.\n490\t\n491\t5\n492\t\n493\tResults and Analysis\n494\t\n495\t5.1\n496\t\n497\tMain End-to-End Results\n498\t\n499\tTable 2 reports anchor-point gains of EGTA-RG\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c2109441-abbc-4d2e-b39b-d82c1f3ffadd", "uuid": "e4f37999-56a9-4d2a-9afa-b709cccb1b68", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T08:07:13.770Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/egta.txt", "content": "the main benefit of extra context in technicaltalk SimulST comes from paper-specific terminology recovery, while uniform context injection can be unreliable.\n• We propose EGTA, an evidence-grounded terminology adaptation framework that restricts\ninference-time adaptation to compact candidate terms selected from document context\nand the current streaming state.\n• We analyze EGTA across end-to-end, cascaded, and generation-only backbones, showing where terminology adaptation provides\nthe most headroom without full-model finetuning.\n\n• Experiments on an ACL technical-talk evaluation suite show consistent improvements\nin XCOMET-XL, named-entity recall, and\nacronym recall, with external ACL60/60-dev\nvalidation and grounding audits supporting\npaper-specific evidence alignment.\n\n2\n\nRelated Work\n\n2.1\n\nSimultaneous Speech Translation\n\nSimultaneous speech translation (SimulST) requires balancing quality and latency while the\nsource speech is still unfolding. Prior work has\nstudied read/write policies such as wait-k, monotonic attention, and information-transport policies,\nas well as evaluation toolkits and latency metrics\nsuch as SimulEval and length-adaptive average lagging (Ma et al., 2019; Arivazhagan et al., 2019;\nMa et al., 2020; Zhang and Feng, 2022; Papi et al.,\n2022). These methods primarily improve segmentation, policy learning, or latency-aware decoding.\nOur work is complementary: we study how to\nuse extra document context when only a subset\nof streaming segments requires paper-specific terminology.\n2.2\n\nContext-Aware and Terminology-Aware\nTranslation\n\nContext-aware translation has been widely studied in document-level MT and ST, including priorsentence context, document-level context, and analyses of whether models actually use contextual\nsignals (Voita et al., 2018; Maruf et al., 2019, 2021;\nZhang et al., 2021; Dabre et al., 2021; Fernandes\net al., 2021). Terminology adaptation has also been\nstudied through lexical constraints, dictionary injection, terminology-aware training, and vocabulary\nbiasing (Hokamp and Liu, 2017; Post and Vilar,\n2018; Dinu et al., 2019). These works show that\nbroader context or external lexical knowledge can\nimprove translation, especially in domain-specific\nsettings.\nSimulST creates a different challenge: context\nmust be useful before the full utterance or document is observed. Uniformly injecting all document terms into every segment may expose the\nmodel to irrelevant context and encourage hallucinated terminology. EGTA therefore differs from\ngeneral document-context methods by treating context as a sparse terminology memory and activating\nit only when the current speech stream provides\nsupporting evidence.\n\n\f2.3\n\nSpeech-Language Models and Contextual\nBiasing\n\nEnd-to-end speech translation and speech-language\nmodels, including Translatotron, SpeechT5, and\nSeamlessM4T, directly map speech to target text\nor unify speech and text modeling (Jia et al., 2019;\nAo et al., 2022; Barrault et al., 2023). In speech\nrecognition, contextual biasing and hotwording are\ncommonly used to improve recognition of rare\nnames, technical terms, and personalized vocabulary (Pundak et al., 2018). EGTA connects these\nideas by decomposing terminology adaptation into\nASR/speech-side and decoder-side decision spaces,\ninstead of treating document context as a uniform\nsignal applied to every segment.\nIn contrast to prior context-aware SimulST work\nthat studies whether context helps at the sentence or\ndocument level, our focus is when context should\nbe activated during streaming inference. EGTA operationalizes this question as terminology-memory\nconstruction, evidence-conditioned candidate selection, and architecture-specific ASR/speech-side\nand decoder-side adaptation.\n\n3\n\nMethod\n\nFigure 1 shows the two-stage EGTA workflow.\nThis section specifies the terminology memory, the\nevidence-conditioned selection algorithm, and the\nconcrete R/G adaptation interfaces used in our systems.\n3.1\n\nProblem Setup\n\nGiven an input speech stream X, a SimulST system incrementally receives audio chunks and emits\ntarget-language text before the full utterance or talk\nis observed. For a streaming segment i, the system\nobserves partial speech input X≤i and produces\ntarget output Yi . In technical talks, we additionally\nassume access to document-level context D, such\nas the paper title, abstract, glossary, or automatically extracted metadata.\nThe goal is to use D to improve terminology\nfidelity without introducing irrelevant terms into\nsegments where the context is not needed. A naive\napproach is to concatenate the whole document\ncontext to every streaming input. However, this\ntreats all segments as equally context-dependent.\nEGTA instead treats document context as a sparse\nterminology source and restricts adaptation to a\nsegment-specific candidate subset.\n\n3.2\n\nTerminology Memory\n\nEGTA converts document context D into a terminology memory TD = {t1 , . . . , tm } containing\npaper-specific terms that are difficult for speech\ntranslation, including acronyms, model and dataset\nnames, method names, organization names, and\ntechnical phrases. The memory is not taken from\nan IWSLT-provided gold glossary. We construct\nit automatically from paper-level context, including titles, abstracts, and available metadata, using a prompt-based Qwen3-30B-Instruct extractor\nserved in FP8. The extractor proposes candidate\nnamed entities and technical terms, after which\nwe normalize terms by case, punctuation, whitespace, and hyphen variants. We keep acronymlike strings, alphanumeric or hyphenated technical\nnames, CamelCase terms, and multi-word technical phrases, while filtering generic function words\nand non-technical metadata. Candidate named entities are therefore treated as a noisy terminology\nlist rather than a gold inventory; EGTA uses local\nspeech evidence to select from this list instead of\ntrusting every extracted term. Each term stores\nsurface forms and tokenizer-level variants for both\nASR/speech-side conditioning and decoder-side token biasing. Appendix A.2 reports memory-size\nand term-type statistics.\n3.3\n\nEvidence-Conditioned Candidate\nSelection\n\nFor each streaming segment, EGTA selects a compact subset of terms from the document memory.\nLet Ei denote the local evidence for segment i,\nincluding the current speech segment, partial transcript or ASR hypothesis, nearby history, and partial target-side state. EGTA forms\nTi = A(TD , Ei ),\n\n(1)\n\nwhere A(·) is the deterministic inference-time procedure in Algorithm 1. The selector normalizes Ei\nwith the same rules as TD , matches surface forms,\nacronyms, and tokenizer-level variants, and ranks\nmatches by exactness, specificity, and recency under a fixed per-segment terminology budget. If the\ncurrent partial hypothesis contains “we evaluate on\nMCIF”, for example, the mention of “MCIF” is\nan evidence event that activates the memory term\nMCIF. Detailed matching rules and prompt formatting are given in Appendix A.3.\nRunning example. Consider a segment whose\npartial ASR hypothesis contains “we evaluate on\n\n\fFigure 1: Overview of EGTA. The bottom panel shows the preparation stage, where document context is converted\noffline into a compact terminology memory. The top panel shows the inference stage: EGTA extracts local evidence\nfrom the current streaming segment, matches it to the terminology memory, selects evidence-supported terms, and\nuses them as inference-time conditioning signals for ASR-side, speech-encoder-side, and decoder-side decisions.\nLocal evidence refers to a cue from the current segment, such as a partial transcript or ASR hypothesis that matches\na term in the terminology memory.\n\nMCIF” while the document memory contains terms\nsuch as MCIF, SimulEval, and Qwen3-Omni. The\nselector treats the observed mention of MCIF as\nlocal evidence, ranks it above unmatched memory terms, and exposes only the selected set to the\ndownstream interfaces. EGTA-R inserts the selected terms into the compact terminology context\nor ASR hotword list, while EGTA-G biases only\nthe corresponding decoder tokens. Unmatched\nmemory terms remain available for later segments\nbut are not activated for the current one.\nThe selected terms define what is exposed to\nASR/speech-side conditioning and decoder-side\nbiasing, but realization is still determined by the\nspeech-conditioned decoder. We therefore use\n“evidence-grounded” as a behavioral claim rather\nthan a hard symbolic guarantee, and validate it\nthrough activation audits, evidence-strength buckets, and shuffled-memory controls in Section 5.4.\n3.4\n\nASR/Speech-Side and Decoder-Side\nAdaptation\n\nEGTA applies selected terms through two interfaces: R(Ti ) for ASR/speech-side conditioning\nand G(Ti ) for decoder-side biasing. EGTA-RG\n\nAlgorithm 1 EGTA inference for streaming segment i\nRequire: document context D, streaming state Ei , terminology budget K, bias strength B\n1: Build or load terminology memory TD from D\n2: Normalize the ASR hypothesis, partial transcript, and\nrecent history in Ei\n3: Match terms in TD by surface form, acronym, or\ntokenizer-level variant\n4: Rank matches by exact match, acronym match, specificity,\nand recency\n5: Select top-K evidence-supported terms Ti\n6: Apply R(Ti ) as ASR hotwords or compact terminology\ncontext\n7: Apply G(Ti ) as decoder-side vocabulary bias with\nstrength B\n8: Decode the next streaming output prefix\n\ncombines both.\nASR/speech-side adaptation. ASR/speech-side\nadaptation helps the system hear or attend to relevant terminology before target decoding. In cascaded systems, R(Ti ) is implemented through ASR\nhotwords or contextual biasing. In end-to-end systems, R(Ti ) is implemented as inference-time terminology conditioning for the speech-language\nmodel rather than as a parameter update. It exposes\nonly selected terms, e.g., Relevant paper terms:\n\n\fMCIF; SimulEval, instead of the full document\ncontext.\nDecoder-side adaptation. Decoder-side adaptation preserves selected terminology during target\ndecoding. For each selected term t ∈ Ti , EGTA\nidentifies target-side token variants and applies a\nvocabulary-level bias. Let zt (v) be the original\nlogit for vocabulary token v at decoding step t.\nEGTA-G modifies it as\nzt′ (v) = zt (v) + B · 1[v ∈ V (Ti )],\n\n(2)\n\nwhere V (Ti ) is the set of vocabulary tokens associated with the selected terms and B is the bias\nstrength. Target-side variants are constructed from\nthe terminology memory and tokenizer outputs,\nnot from test references. This biasing rule is deliberately simple: our goal is not to introduce a new\nconstrained-decoding algorithm, but to test whether\ndocument terms should be activated selectively under streaming evidence. We therefore compare\nEGTA-G with stronger alternatives, including uniform full-memory context and Global-G, which\napplies decoder-side bias to all memory terms without evidence-conditioned selection. As shown in\nSection 5.3 and Appendix A.6, stronger all-term\nbias increases over-biasing risk and can degrade\nBLEU and latency, while selected-term bias gives\na better recall–quality–latency trade-off. Unlike\nglobal terminology biasing, EGTA-G biases only\nevidence-selected terms, limiting over-biasing on\nunrelated segments.\nFull EGTA-RG. When both interfaces are available, EGTA decodes with\nYi = Mθ (X≤i ; R(Ti ), G(Ti )).\n\nR(Ti ) interface\n\nG(Ti ) interface\n\nQwen3-Omni E2E compact term context decoder logit bias\nCascade ASR–MT ASR hotwords\nMT vocabulary bias\nSeamlessM4T\n–\ndecoder-side EGTA-G\n\nTable 1: Concrete EGTA instantiations across backbones.\n\n4\n\nExperimental Setup\n\n4.1\n\nDatasets\n\nWe evaluate EGTA on an ACL technical-talk\nSimulST evaluation suite consisting of MCIF-dev\nand ACL60/60-dev. Both subsets are built from\ntechnical conference talks with paper-level context,\nmaking them suitable for evaluating terminology\nadaptation under streaming speech evidence.\nMCIF-dev is derived from MCIF (Multimodal\nCrosslingual Instruction Following), a multilingual\nbenchmark based on scientific talks (Papi et al.,\n2025). We pair its speech and references with\npaper-level metadata, including titles, abstracts,\nand extracted terminology, and use the resulting 21talk, 919-segment technical-talk subset as the main\nbenchmark for full latency, ablation, and grounding\nanalyses.\nACL60/60-dev is used as an external technicaltalk benchmark. It contains 5 ACL talks and 468\ngold-segmented segments with official En→Zh\nand En→De references. It also provides tagged\nterminology for both target languages, allowing\nterminology-sensitive evaluation beyond MCIFdev. We use the same terminology extraction,\nnormalization, candidate selection, and EGTA-RG\nB=2 configuration without additional fine-tuning.\n\n(3)\n\nHere R(Ti ) improves access to relevant terminology in the speech-understanding stage, while G(Ti )\npreserves selected terms through token-level biasing.\n3.5\n\nBackbone\n\nArchitecture Instantiations\n\nTable 1 summarizes the concrete interfaces used in\neach backbone. All instantiations share the same\nselected term set Ti ; they differ only in how R(Ti )\nand G(Ti ) are exposed by the model.\nThe Qwen3-Omni end-to-end setting is our main\nsystem. The cascade setting diagnoses how much\nheadroom remains when ASR-side hotwording is\nalready available, and SeamlessM4T provides a\ngeneration-only transfer check when the R(Ti ) interface is unavailable.\n\n4.2\n\nSystems and Configurations\n\nFor end-to-end SimulST, we use a fine-tuned\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B audio-text LLM as the\nbackbone. Following our IWSLT system setup,\nthe audio encoder is kept frozen, the non-text generation modules are disabled, and only languageside LoRA adapters are used to teach streaming\nread/write behavior. At inference time, the backbone is served with vLLM using greedy decoding and a bounded dialogue history. The backbone checkpoint, chunk schedule, decoding parameters, and evaluation talks are fixed across variants;\nvariants differ only in the inference-time terminology interface. The baseline receives the streaming\nspeech input and task instruction without document\nterminology adaptation. We additionally include a\n\n\funiform-context baseline, which injects the full perpaper terminology memory into every streaming\nsegment without evidence-conditioned selection or\ndecoder-side biasing. This baseline tests whether\nsimply exposing document terminology to every\nsegment is sufficient.\nEGTA-R adds a compact terminology block selected from the document memory; EGTA-G applies decoder-side vocabulary bias to terminology tokens; and EGTA-RG combines both channels. Unless otherwise specified, our recommended\nend-to-end configuration is EGTA-RG with bias\nstrength B = 2.\nWe also evaluate EGTA in a cascaded ASR–MT\nsetting for architecture analysis. We use Qwen3ASR-1.7B as the ASR front end and pass the selected terms as ASR hotwords/contextual-biasing\nterms for EGTA-R; EGTA-G is implemented\nthrough MT decoder vocabulary bias. Finally, we\nevaluate SeamlessM4T-v2-large as a generationonly backbone validation. Since this backbone\ndoes not expose the same editable terminologyprompting interface used for EGTA-R, we instantiate only EGTA-G. To test whether gains are paperspecific, we additionally use a shuffled-memory\ncontrol that pairs each segment with terminology\nmemory from a mismatched paper.\n4.3\n\nMetrics and Diagnostics\n\nWe report BLEU, chrF, XCOMET-XL, NERclean\nrecall, acronym recall, and LongLAALCU latency. BLEU and chrF measure surface overlap,\nXCOMET-XL provides a neural quality estimate,\nand lower LongLAALCU indicates lower latency.\nNERclean recall is computed over cleaned paperspecific entities after normalizing case, punctuation,\nwhitespace, hyphenation, and tokenizer artifacts;\nacronym recall is computed over uppercase and\nalphanumeric paper terms. We use terminology recall as the primary metric because omission or mistranslation of paper-specific terms is the main failure mode in technical-talk SimulST. Since surfaceform precision depends on whether a reference\npreserves the same term realization, precision/F1style matching is treated as a conservative diagnostic, while possible over-generation is analyzed\nthrough unsupported-activation audits, shuffledmemory controls, and Global-G stress tests.\nFor the main end-to-end experiments, we evaluate five latency operating points; the anchor point\nis used for detailed comparison, ablation, and\nshuffled-memory control. In addition to aggregate\n\nSet\n\nLang. ∆BLEU ∆XCOMET ∆NER ∆Acro ∆LAAL\n\nMCIF-dev\nZh\nMCIF-dev\nDe\nACL60/60-dev Zh\nACL60/60-dev De\n\n+1.05\n+0.59\n+0.94\n+0.56\n\n+.019\n+.006\n+.022\n+.005\n\n+.212\n+.266\n+.113\n+.214\n\n+.099\n+.171\n+.119\n+.100\n\n-46\n-44\n–\n–\n\nTable 2: Anchor-point gains of EGTA-RG B=2 over\nthe baseline on the ACL technical-talk evaluation suite.\nNER denotes NERclean recall. LAAL is reported\nfor MCIF-dev, where the streaming-yaml protocol is\nmatched across systems. Full absolute scores are reported in Appendix A.1.\n\nmetrics, we conduct activation audits, evidencestrength bucket analysis, and shuffled-memory controls to validate whether realized terminology usage\nis supported by speech-conditioned evidence rather\nthan generic context exposure.\n\n5\n\nResults and Analysis\n\n5.1\n\nMain End-to-End Results\n\nTable 2 reports anchor-point gains of EGTA-RG", "numLines": 400, "startLine": 100, "totalLines": 1428}}}
