{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-83c53656e8218950", "type": "tool_result", "content": "500\tover the baseline on the ACL technical-talk evaluation suite. The main pattern is consistent across\n501\tboth datasets and both language directions: EGTARG improves terminology-sensitive metrics, while\n502\tmaintaining or improving overall translation quality.\n503\tOn MCIF-dev, EGTA-RG improves all reported\n504\tanchor-point metrics on both En→Zh and En→De.\n505\tThe largest gains appear on terminology fidelity:\n506\tNERclean recall improves by +0.212/+0.266 and\n507\tacronym recall by +0.099/+0.171, while XCOMETXL also increases by +0.019/+0.006. Latency\n508\tis slightly reduced on both directions, with\n509\tLongLAALCU decreasing by 46 ms and 44 ms.\n510\tACL60/60-dev provides an external validation of the same trend without additional finetuning.\n511\tEGTA-RG improves NERclean recall by +0.113/+0.214 and acronym recall by\n512\t+0.119/+0.100 on En→Zh and En→De. On\n513\tEn→Zh, it also improves BLEU by +0.94 and\n514\tXCOMET-XL by +0.022 over the baseline and\n515\toutperforms uniform context on overall quality.\n516\tWe further conduct paired bootstrap resampling\n517\twith 5,000 samples at both segment and talk\n518\tlevels on MCIF-dev. The terminology-fidelity\n519\tgains are statistically robust on both language\n520\tpairs: NERclean recall and acronym recall improve significantly on En→Zh and En→De (p <\n521\t0.001). Appendix A.5 reports ACL60/60-dev\n522\tsignificance details, and Appendix A.8 reports\n523\treference-supported terminology matching. Over-\n524\t\n525\t\fAnalysis\n526\t\n527\tMain observation\n528\t\n529\tTakeaway\n530\t\n531\tUniform con- Partial gains;\n532\tbelow Selection\n533\ttext\n534\tEGTA-RG\n535\thelps\n536\tGlobal-G B = Zh BLEU −2.1; latency Over-bias\n537\t5\n538\tcollapse\n539\tstress\n540\tCascaded\n541\tZh: +0.25 BLEU, +1.46 Less\n542\theadSimulST\n543\tNER\n544\troom\n545\tSeamlessM4T De NER: 36.7→51.7\n546\tDecoder transfer\n547\t\n548\tTable 3: Auxiliary analyses testing always-on context,\n549\tover-biasing, and architectural transfer. Full metrics are\n550\tprovided in Appendices A.6 and A.9.\n551\t\n552\tall, these results support our central hypothesis:\n553\textra document context is most useful when converted into selective terminology adaptation rather\n554\tthan injected uniformly as general semantic context.\n555\t\n556\t5.2\n557\t\n558\tEnd-to-End Latency–Quality Frontier\n559\t\n560\tOn MCIF-dev, we further evaluate EGTA-RG\n561\tacross five latency operating points. Figure 2\n562\tshows the end-to-end latency–quality frontier on\n563\tXCOMET-XL and NERclean recall. EGTA-RG consistently outperforms the baseline on both metrics\n564\tacross operating points, and is generally stronger\n565\tthan the uniform-context variant, especially on terminology recall. This indicates that simply exposing the full terminology memory to every segment\n566\trecovers part of the benefit, but does not provide the\n567\tsame terminology–latency trade-off as evidenceconditioned R+G composition. We report only endto-end systems in this figure; cascaded systems are\n568\tanalyzed separately in Section 5.3 to avoid mixing\n569\tdifferent latency sources and terminology-recall\n570\tprotocols.\n571\tAcross the five operating points, EGTA-RG improves the En→Zh baseline by +1.31 BLEU, +2.30\n572\tchrF, +0.0241 XCOMET-XL, +0.255 NERclean recall, and +0.117 acronym recall on average, while\n573\treducing LongLAALCU by 43 ms. On En→De,\n574\tEGTA-RG improves BLEU by +0.81, XCOMETXL by +0.0055, NERclean recall by +0.277, and\n575\tacronym recall by +0.154 on average. XCOMETXL, NERclean , and acronym recall improve at all\n576\tfive operating points, and the positive average\n577\tBLEU gain suggests that the terminology improvements do not come at the cost of overall translation\n578\tquality.\n579\t\n580\tDiagnostic\n581\t\n582\tEn→Zh\n583\t\n584\tEn→De\n585\t\n586\tLocal/ref audit support\n587\tSame-paper audit support\n588\tUnsupported activation\n589\t\n590\t86.4%\n591\t96.0%\n592\t4.0%\n593\t\n594\t86.1%\n595\t93.9%\n596\t6.1%\n597\t\n598\tHigh evid. ∆chrF / ∆NER\n599\t+3.7 / +27.7 +1.8 / +16.2\n600\tMedium evid. ∆chrF / ∆NER +6.9 / +59.6 +3.2 / +58.2\n601\tLow/none ∆chrF / Unsup. act. +0.3 / 39.5% +0.4 / 27.3%\n602\t\n603\tTable 4: Grounding validation. The first block audits\n604\tlocal/reference support, same-paper support, and unsupported activation; references are used only for post-hoc\n605\tvalidation. The second block reports gains by evidence\n606\tstrength. ∆NER is in percentage points; Unsup. act.\n607\tdenotes unsupported activation rate.\n608\t\n609\t5.3\n610\t\n611\tAdditional Analyses\n612\t\n613\tTable 3 summarizes four auxiliary analyses. Uniform context exposes the full paper terminology\n614\tmemory to every segment. Global-G applies\n615\tdecoder-side vocabulary bias to all memory terms\n616\twithout evidence-conditioned selection and serves\n617\tas an over-bias stress test rather than a matched\n618\toperating-point baseline.\n619\tTogether, these checks show that EGTA is not\n620\tmerely stronger context injection: always-on context or biasing is less stable, while architecture\n621\tchecks show that gains depend on remaining terminology headroom. Shuffled-memory controls\n622\tfurther suggest that the improvements are paperspecific rather than generic biasing effects.\n623\t5.4\n624\t\n625\tGrounding Validation\n626\t\n627\tTable 4 summarizes three grounding diagnostics.\n628\tEGTA usually activates terms supported by the\n629\tcurrent speech stream, and its largest gains appear\n630\tin segments with explicit evidence.\n631\tActivation support. The first block audits\n632\twhether activated terms have post-hoc evidence.\n633\tLocal/reference audit support counts an activation\n634\tas supported when the normalized term appears in\n635\tlocal streaming evidence, such as the ASR hypothesis or nearby transcript, or in the segment-level\n636\treference. The reference is used only for validation, not for candidate selection or decoding. Samepaper audit support additionally allows the term to\n637\tappear elsewhere in the same talk evidence. Unsupported activations account for only 4.0% / 6.1%\n638\tof activations.\n639\tEvidence-strength buckets. We bucket segments before scoring outputs: high evidence has\n640\tan exact normalized match in the local hypothe-\n641\t\n642\t\fBaseline\n643\t\n644\tWith-context (R only)\n645\t\n646\t0.78\n647\t\n648\tEGTA-RG B=2 (ours)\n649\t\n650\t0.5\n651\t\n652\tNERclean recall\n653\t\n654\tXCOMET-XL\n655\t\n656\t0.77\n657\t0.76\n658\t0.75\n659\t0.74\n660\t\n661\t0.4\n662\t\n663\t0.3\n664\t\n665\t0.2\n666\t\n667\t0.73\n668\t1600\n669\t\n670\t1800\n671\t\n672\t2000\n673\t\n674\t2200\n675\t\n676\t2400\n677\t\n678\t2600\n679\t\n680\t1600\n681\t\n682\tLongLAAL_CU (ms) - En → Zh\n683\t\n684\t1800\n685\t\n686\t2000\n687\t\n688\t2200\n689\t\n690\t2400\n691\t\n692\t2600\n693\t\n694\tLongLAAL_CU (ms) - En → Zh\n695\t\n696\tNERclean recall\n697\t\n698\tXCOMET-XL\n699\t\n700\t0.86\n701\t0.84\n702\t0.82\n703\t0.80\n704\t\n705\t0.6\n706\t0.5\n707\t0.4\n708\t0.3\n709\t\n710\t0.78\n711\t1400\n712\t\n713\t1600\n714\t\n715\t1800\n716\t\n717\t2000\n718\t\n719\t1400\n720\t\n721\tLongLAAL_CU (ms) - En → De\n722\t\n723\t1600\n724\t\n725\t1800\n726\t\n727\t2000\n728\t\n729\tLongLAAL_CU (ms) - En → De\n730\t\n731\tFigure 2: End-to-end latency–quality frontier on MCIF-dev. Each marker corresponds to one latency operating\n732\tpoint. The top row shows En→Zh and the bottom row shows En→De; the left column reports XCOMET-XL and\n733\tthe right column reports NERclean recall. EGTA-RG B=2 consistently improves XCOMET-XL and terminology\n734\trecall over the baseline, and generally outperforms the uniform-context variant on terminology recall.\n735\t\n736\tsis or nearby transcript; medium evidence has an\n737\tacronym, partial phrase, or tokenizer-level variant\n738\tmatch; low/none has no such evidence. These buckets are computed from source-side evidence and\n739\tthe terminology memory, not from system outputs.\n740\tHigh- and medium-evidence segments show the\n741\tlargest NER gains, while low/none-evidence segments show only small chrF changes (+0.3/+0.4),\n742\tsuggesting limited over-biasing on unrelated segments.\n743\t\n744\t6\n745\t\n746\tConclusion\n747\t\n748\tWe presented EGTA, a lightweight inferencetime framework for evidence-conditioned terminology adaptation in technical-talk SimulST. Across\n749\tMCIF-dev and ACL60/60-dev, EGTA improves\n750\tterminology recall while maintaining overall translation quality. Latency-frontier results, shuffledmemory controls, and activation audits suggest that\n751\textra context is most useful when exposed as selected terminology evidence rather than injected\n752\tuniformly into every segment.\n753\t\n754\tLimitations\n755\tShuffled-memory\n756\tcontrol. The\n757\tshuffledmemory control verifies that the gains require\n758\tthe correct paper memory. On En→De, the\n759\tanchor NER gain drops from +0.266 with correct\n760\tmemory to +0.012 with shuffled memory, and the\n761\tmedium-evidence NER gain drops from +58.2\n762\tto +7.5 points. Thus, grounding is a behavioral\n763\tproperty that emerges when speech-conditioned\n764\tdecoding is paired with the correct paper-specific\n765\tterminology memory.\n766\t\n767\tThis work focuses on technical-talk SimulST,\n768\twhere document-level paper context is available\n769\tand terminology fidelity is important; open-domain,\n770\tinformal, and low-context settings remain to be\n771\tstudied. EGTA also depends on terminologymemory quality: missing or irrelevant extracted\n772\tterms can weaken both ASR/speech-side and\n773\tdecoder-side adaptation.\n774\tThe grounding criterion is behavioral and auditbased rather than enforced by a separately trained\n775\t\n776\t\fsymbolic evidence detector. The current selector\n777\tuses normalized surface matching, so severe ASR\n778\terrors or phonetic variants may prevent term activation; future work should add phonetic or fuzzy\n779\tmatching.\n780\tOur evaluation emphasizes automatic\n781\tterminology-recall metrics,\n782\tcomplemented\n783\tby activation audits, shuffled-memory controls,\n784\tover-bias diagnostics, and precision/F1-style\n785\tsurface matching. We do not include full human\n786\tevaluation of terminology correctness, perceived\n787\tusefulness, or harmful wrong insertions. Finally,\n788\tboth MCIF-dev and ACL60/60-dev are technical\n789\tconference-talk subsets, and our SeamlessM4T\n790\tvalidation covers only decoder-side EGTA-G\n791\tbecause the backbone does not expose the editable\n792\tEGTA-R interface.\n793\t\n794\tEthical Considerations\n795\tEGTA aims to improve terminology fidelity\n796\tin technical-talk SimulST by preserving names,\n797\tacronyms, datasets, and method terms. However,\n798\tterminology adaptation can amplify errors if document context is mismatched, outdated, or maliciously constructed. The system may still produce\n799\tmistranslations, omissions, or hallucinated terms,\n800\tespecially in low-evidence segments or unreliable\n801\tspeech conditions, and should not be used as the\n802\tsole mechanism in high-stakes settings without human oversight. Our experiments use technical-talk\n803\tdata and paper-level context and do not involve\n804\tpersonal profiling beyond the context required for\n805\ttranslation.\n806\t\n807\tReferences\n808\tJunyi Ao, Rui Wang, Long Zhou, Chengyi Wang, Shuo\n809\tRen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Tom Ko, Qing Li, Yu Zhang,\n810\tZhihua Wei, Yao Qian, Jinyu Li, and Furu Wei.\n811\t2022. SpeechT5: Unified-modal encoder-decoder\n812\tpre-training for spoken language processing. In Proceedings of the 60th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics, pages 5723–\n813\t5738, Dublin, Ireland. Association for Computational\n814\tLinguistics.\n815\tNaveen Arivazhagan, Colin Cherry, Wolfgang\n816\tMacherey, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Semih Yavuz, Ruoming Pang, Wei Li, and Colin Raffel. 2019. Monotonic\n817\tinfinite lookback attention for simultaneous machine\n818\ttranslation. In Proceedings of the 57th Annual\n819\tMeeting of the Association for Computational\n820\tLinguistics, pages 1313–1323, Florence, Italy.\n821\tAssociation for Computational Linguistics.\n822\t\n823\tLoïc Barrault, Yu-An Chung, Mariano Cora Meglioli,\n824\tDavid Dale, Ning Dong, Paul-Ambroise Duquenne,\n825\tHady Elsahar, Hongyu Gong, Kevin Heffernan, John\n826\tHoffman, and 1 others. 2023. Seamlessm4t: Massively multilingual & multimodal machine translation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2308.11596.\n827\tRaj Dabre, Aizhan Imankulova, and Masahiro Kaneko.\n828\t2021. Studying the impact of document-level context on simultaneous neural machine translation. In\n829\tProceedings of Machine Translation Summit XVIII:\n830\tResearch Track, pages 202–214, Virtual. Association\n831\tfor Machine Translation in the Americas.\n832\tGeorgiana Dinu, Prashant Mathur, Marcello Federico,\n833\tand Yaser Al-Onaizan. 2019. Training neural machine translation to apply terminology constraints. In\n834\tProceedings of the 57th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics, pages 3063–\n835\t3068, Florence, Italy. Association for Computational\n836\tLinguistics.\n837\tPatrick Fernandes, Kayo Yin, Graham Neubig, and André F. T. Martins. 2021. Measuring and increasing\n838\tcontext usage in context-aware machine translation.\n839\tIn Proceedings of the 59th Annual Meeting of the\n840\tAssociation for Computational Linguistics and the\n841\t11th International Joint Conference on Natural Language Processing (Volume 1: Long Papers), pages\n842\t6467–6478, Online. Association for Computational\n843\tLinguistics.\n844\tChris Hokamp and Qun Liu. 2017. Lexically constrained decoding for sequence generation using grid\n845\tbeam search. In Proceedings of the 55th Annual\n846\tM