logy\n1103\tmemory. The R-prompt exposes a compact top-K term\n1104\tlist, while G-bias candidates are vocabulary-bias candidates derived from the filtered memory.\n1105\tTerm type\n1106\t\n1107\tMCIF-dev\n1108\t\n1109\tACL60/60-dev\n1110\t\n1111\tAcronym-like\n1112\t32 (15.0%)\n1113\tAlphanumeric / hyphenated\n1114\t6 (2.8%)\n1115\tCamelCase / model or dataset\n1116\t4 (1.9%)\n1117\tMulti-word technical\n1118\t31 (14.5%)\n1119\tNamed entity: person\n1120\t104 (48.6%)\n1121\tNamed entity: organization\n1122\t37 (17.3%)\n1123\t\n1124\t6 (18.8%)\n1125\t2 (6.2%)\n1126\t0 (0.0%)\n1127\t9 (28.1%)\n1128\t15 (46.9%)\n1129\t0 (0.0%)\n1130\t\n1131\tTotal\n1132\t\n1133\t32 (100%)\n1134\t\n1135\t214 (100%)\n1136\t\n1137\tTable 7: Distribution of filtered terminology-memory\n1138\ttypes. The retained categories include acronym-like\n1139\tstrings, alphanumeric or hyphenated technical names,\n1140\tCamelCase spans, model or dataset names, multi-word\n1141\ttechnical phrases, and named entities.\n1142\t\n1143\ttarget tokenizer outputs, not from segment-level\n1144\ttest references. Acronyms, model names, dataset\n1145\tnames, and alphanumeric terms are kept as copyable forms across target languages. When a target alias is available in the memory, it is included\n1146\tas an additional variant; otherwise, the normalized source form and its tokenizer-level variants\n1147\tare used. Multi-token terms contribute their corresponding token ids to the bias set. For EGTA-R,\n1148\tselected terms are inserted into a compact terminology block attached to the task instruction and\n1149\t\n1150\tupdated for each streaming segment, rather than\n1151\texposing the full document memory.\n1152\tBackbone and decoding details. The Qwen3Omni backbone follows our IWSLT 2026 system\n1153\tsetup. We use Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B with the audio encoder frozen and LoRA adapters inserted\n1154\tonly into the LLM/Thinker module; the vision\n1155\tand speech-synthesis modules are disabled. We\n1156\ttrain one LoRA checkpoint per target language on\n1157\t220K retained chunk-level examples constructed\n1158\tfrom LibriSpeech, Common Voice 17.0, CoVoST2,\n1159\tand VoxPopuli. LoRA is applied to the q_proj,\n1160\tk_proj, v_proj, and o_proj modules with rank\n1161\t16, alpha 32, and dropout 0.05. The peak learning\n1162\trates are 1 × 10−4 for En→Zh and 5 × 10−5 for\n1163\tEn→De, with global batch size 128 and 3 training\n1164\tepochs on 8 NVIDIA A100 GPUs. At inference\n1165\ttime, the model is served with vLLM using greedy\n1166\tdecoding; the streaming agent keeps the most recent 16 dialogue turns or 20 seconds of audio history. The latency operating points are controlled by\n1167\tthe audio chunk size while all compared variants\n1168\tuse the same backbone checkpoint and decoding\n1169\tsettings.\n1170\tLatency and grounding audit. LongLAALCU\n1171\tfollows an LAAL-style computation over committed output units, using source chunk timestamps\n1172\tand emitted target prefixes. All systems compared\n1173\tat the same operating point use the same chunk\n1174\tschedule and segmentation policy, so latency differences reflect decoding and adaptation behavior\n1175\trather than different input chunking. In grounding\n1176\taudits, an activation is counted as local/reference\n1177\taudit supported if its normalized surface form,\n1178\tacronym, or accepted tokenizer-level variant appears in either the local hypothesis available during\n1179\tstreaming or the segment reference used for posthoc validation. It is counted as same-paper audit\n1180\t\n1181\t\fLang.\n1182\t\n1183\tMetric\n1184\t\n1185\t∆\n1186\t\n1187\tEn→Zh\n1188\tEn→Zh\n1189\tEn→De\n1190\tEn→De\n1191\t\n1192\tNERclean\n1193\tAcro\n1194\tNERclean\n1195\tAcro\n1196\t\n1197\t+0.212\n1198\t+0.099\n1199\t+0.266\n1200\t+0.171\n1201\t\n1202\t95% CI\n1203\t\n1204\tp\n1205\t\n1206\t[+0.140, +0.285] < 0.001\n1207\t[+0.033, +0.168] 0.004\n1208\t[+0.180, +0.351] < 0.001\n1209\t[+0.103, +0.243] < 0.001\n1210\t\n1211\tTable 8: Paired-bootstrap significance for terminologyfidelity metrics at the anchor operating point. ∆ denotes\n1212\tEGTA-RG B=2 minus the baseline. Confidence intervals and p-values are computed with 5,000 segmentlevel bootstrap resamples.\n1213\t\n1214\tsupported if the same normalized term appears elsewhere in the same talk evidence. An unsupported\n1215\tactivation is an activated paper term without local/reference support under these matching rules;\n1216\tnear matches are counted only when they normalize\n1217\tto an accepted surface, acronym, or tokenizer-level\n1218\tvariant.\n1219\tA.4\n1220\t\n1221\tStatistical Robustness of Terminology\n1222\tGains\n1223\t\n1224\tWe conduct paired bootstrap resampling with 5,000\n1225\tsamples at both segment and talk levels to assess\n1226\twhether the terminology-fidelity gains are robust.\n1227\tTable 8 reports the results for the two primary terminology metrics. NERclean recall and acronym\n1228\trecall improve significantly on both language pairs,\n1229\tsupporting our use of terminology recall as the primary evidence for EGTA’s effect.\n1230\tA.5\n1231\t\n1232\tACL60/60-dev External Validation\n1233\tDetails\n1234\t\n1235\tACL60/60-dev contains 5 ACL talks and 468 goldsegmented segments. We run the same anchor\n1236\tEGTA-RG B=2 configuration used for MCIF-dev\n1237\twithout additional fine-tuning. Since this split does\n1238\tnot provide the same gold streaming-yaml protocol as MCIF-dev, ACL60/60-dev latency is used\n1239\tonly as an internal relative diagnostic; the main\n1240\ttext focuses on text quality and terminology fidelity. Segment-level paired bootstrap shows significant En→Zh gains in XCOMET-XL (p = .006),\n1241\tacronym recall (p = .04), and tagged-terminology\n1242\trecall (p = .001). On En→De, NERclean and\n1243\tacronym gains are significant at both segment and\n1244\ttalk levels.\n1245\tA.6\n1246\t\n1247\tUniform Context and Global Bias Stress\n1248\tTests\n1249\t\n1250\tWe compare EGTA-RG against two stronger alternatives to test whether the gains can be explained by simply exposing more terminology or\n1251\t\n1252\tLang. System\n1253\t\n1254\tBLEU\n1255\t\n1256\tchrF\n1257\t\n1258\tXCOMET GoldTag\n1259\t\n1260\tZh\n1261\tZh\n1262\tZh\n1263\t\n1264\tBaseline\n1265\tUniform\n1266\tEGTA-RG B=2\n1267\t\n1268\t42.35\n1269\t41.24\n1270\t43.29\n1271\t\n1272\t35.91\n1273\t35.74\n1274\t37.28\n1275\t\n1276\t0.7337\n1277\t0.7289\n1278\t0.7554\n1279\t\n1280\t0.709\n1281\t0.728\n1282\t0.746\n1283\t\n1284\tDe\n1285\tDe\n1286\tDe\n1287\t\n1288\tBaseline\n1289\tUniform\n1290\tEGTA-RG B=2\n1291\t\n1292\t28.29\n1293\t28.50\n1294\t28.85\n1295\t\n1296\t61.00\n1297\t60.97\n1298\t61.17\n1299\t\n1300\t0.8214\n1301\t0.8123\n1302\t0.8263\n1303\t\n1304\t0.656\n1305\t0.631\n1306\t0.642\n1307\t\n1308\tTable 9: ACL60/60-dev external validation. GoldTag denotes recall over official tagged terminology. ACL60/60dev latency is used only as an internal diagnostic because its streaming-yaml protocol differs from MCIFdev.\n1309\t\n1310\tSystem\n1311\t\n1312\tBLEU chrF XCOMET NER Acro LAAL\n1313\t\n1314\tBaseline\n1315\tUniform\n1316\tGlobal-G B=5\n1317\tEGTA-RG B=2\n1318\t\n1319\t43.31\n1320\t44.08\n1321\t41.21\n1322\t44.36\n1323\t\n1324\t36.67\n1325\t38.35\n1326\t35.36\n1327\t38.56\n1328\t\n1329\t0.7550\n1330\t0.7628\n1331\t0.7364\n1332\t0.7740\n1333\t\n1334\t0.268 0.680\n1335\t0.424 0.739\n1336\t0.398 0.685\n1337\t0.480 0.779\n1338\t\n1339\t1763\n1340\t1779\n1341\t1318\n1342\t1717\n1343\t\n1344\tTable 10: Uniform-context and global-bias stress\n1345\ttest on En→Zh.\n1346\tEGTA-RG B=2 provides the\n1347\tbest recall–quality–latency trade-off; LAAL denotes\n1348\tLongLAALCU in milliseconds.\n1349\t\n1350\tapplying stronger decoder bias. The uniformcontext baseline injects the full per-paper terminology memory into every streaming segment without\n1351\tevidence-conditioned selection or decoder-side biasing. Global-G applies decoder-side bias to all\n1352\tdocument terms for every segment without the\n1353\tASR/speech-side prompt.\n1354\tTable 10 summarizes the En→Zh anchor comparison. Uniform context recovers part of the gain,\n1355\tshowing that document terminology is useful, but\n1356\tit does not match EGTA-RG on the joint recall–\n1357\tquality–latency trade-off. Global all-term biasing\n1358\tshows a clear over-bias failure mode when the bias\n1359\tis too strong: at B = 5, BLEU drops below the\n1360\tbaseline and latency collapses. In contrast, EGTARG with B = 2 achieves the strongest overall\n1361\ttrade-off among the tested configurations.\n1362\tWe also conduct a bias-strength sweep on\n1363\tEn→Zh. G-only biasing improves terminology\n1364\trecall as B increases, but aggressive biasing eventually harms overall quality. Once the ASR/speechside prompt is active, increasing from EGTA-RG\n1365\tB=2 to B=3 yields diminishing returns: NER recall\n1366\tdoes not improve, while BLEU, XCOMET-XL, and\n1367\tacronym recall decrease. We therefore use B = 2\n1368\tas a practical trade-off between terminology recall\n1369\tand over-biasing risk.\n1370\t\n1371\t\fCondition\n1372\tCorrect memory\n1373\tShuffled memory\n1374\t\n1375\tAnchor ∆NER Medium-evid. ∆NER\n1376\t+0.266\n1377\t+0.012\n1378\t\n1379\t+58.2\n1380\t+7.5\n1381\t\n1382\tTable 11: Shuffled-memory control on En→De. ∆NER\n1383\tis reported against the baseline. The large drop under shuffled memory indicates that the gains depend\n1384\ton matching the correct paper memory to the current\n1385\tspeech stream.\n1386\t\n1387\tA.7\n1388\t\n1389\tShuffled-Memory Control\n1390\t\n1391\tThe shuffled-memory control tests whether terminology gains require matching the correct paper\n1392\tmemory to the current speech stream. Table 11 reports the shuffled-memory diagnostic used in Section 5.4.\n1393\tA.8\n1394\t\n1395\tReference-Supported Terminology\n1396\tMatching\n1397\t\n1398\tWe further compute a reference-supported terminology matching diagnostic using the same normalization protocol as NERclean . Gold terms are\n1399\tpaper terms preserved in the reference, and predicted terms are paper terms realized in the system output. Because this diagnostic depends on\n1400\treference-preserved surface forms, it is conservative and should be interpreted as a complementary\n1401\tsurface-form analysis rather than as a direct measure of harmful over-generation. We do not use\n1402\tit as a direct over-generation measure because a\n1403\tsystem output can realize a valid paper term even\n1404\twhen the single reference does not preserve the\n1405\tsame surface form.\n1406\tUnder this protocol, EGTA-RG improves microF1 from 0.625 to 0.839 on En→Zh and from 0.575\n1407\tto 0.753 on En→De. This suggests that EGTA improves reference-supported terminology coverage\n1408\tunder a strict matching criterion.\n1409\tWe therefore use this diagnostic as a complement to NERclean , acronym recall, activation audits, shuffled-memory controls, and over-bias stress\n1410\ttests, rather than as the primary ranking metric.\n1411\tA.9\n1412\t\n1413\tSeamlessM4T Quality-Cost\n1414\tDecomposition\n1415\t\n1416\tSection 5.3 reports terminology-fidelity transfer to SeamlessM4T-v2-large.\n1417\tFull quality metrics show small corpus-level changes:\n1418\tBLEU/chrF/XCOMET change by −0.54/ −\n1419\t0.33/ − 0.0028 on En→Zh and −0.36/ − 0.89/ −\n1420\t0.0084 on En→De. The cost is largely memoryagnostic: shuffled memory causes a similar quality\n1421\t\n1422\tchange while removing most terminology gain. On\n1423\tsegments whose references contain paper terms,\n1424\tEGTA-G improves chrF by +1.12 on En→Zh and\n1425\t+1.02 on En→De, with En→De XCOMET also\n1426\tincreasing by +0.0071.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-